{"parse":{"title":"Tezi Altarpiece","pageid":31590105,"revid":845983340,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vevent\" style=\"width:22em;width: 22em; line-height: 1.4em; text-align: left; float:right;\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" class=\"summary\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;font-size: 125%; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic\">Tezi Altarpiece</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Pala_tezi,.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Pala tezi,.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Pala_tezi%2C.jpg/300px-Pala_tezi%2C.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"398\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Pala_tezi%2C.jpg/450px-Pala_tezi%2C.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Pala_tezi%2C.jpg/600px-Pala_tezi%2C.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1083\" data-file-height=\"1435\" /></a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Artist</th><td class=\"attendee\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/Pietro_Perugino\" title=\"Pietro Perugino\">Pietro Perugino</a> and workshop</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Year</th><td>\nc. 1500</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Medium</th><td class=\"category\">\nOil on panel</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Dimensions</th><td>\n180&#160;cm&#32;\u00d7&#160;158&#160;cm&#32;(71&#160;in&#32;\u00d7&#160;62&#160;in)</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Location</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Galleria_Nazionale_dell%27Umbria\" title=\"Galleria Nazionale dell&#39;Umbria\">Galleria Nazionale dell'Umbria</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Perugia\" title=\"Perugia\">Perugia</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Italy\" title=\"Italy\">Italy</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>The <i><b>Tezi Altarpiece</b></i> (Italian: <i>Pala Tezi</i>)  is a painting   by the Italian  Renaissance painter   <a href=\"/wiki/Pietro_Perugino\" title=\"Pietro Perugino\">Pietro Perugino</a>, housed in the <a href=\"/wiki/Galleria_Nazionale_dell%27Umbria\" title=\"Galleria Nazionale dell&#39;Umbria\">Galleria Nazionale dell'Umbria</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Perugia\" title=\"Perugia\">Perugia</a>, Italy.  The work was once associated to a single predella panel portraying the <i>Last Supper</i> (18&#160;cm \u00d7&#160;121&#160;cm or 7.1&#160;in \u00d7&#160;47.6&#160;in), now at the <a href=\"/wiki/Gem%C3%A4ldegalerie,_Berlin\" title=\"Gem\u00e4ldegalerie, Berlin\"> Gem\u00e4ldegalerie</a> of Berlin.\n</p><p>The painting was executed for the Tezi Chapel in the church of Sant'Agostino in <a href=\"/wiki/Perugia\" title=\"Perugia\">Perugia</a>. After that monastic institute was suppressed under the Napoleonic domination of Italy, it was acquired by the Umbrian Gallery.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Style\">Style</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Tezi_Altarpiece&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Style\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The panel shows the Madonna and Child on a cloud in the sky, flanked by <a href=\"/wiki/St._Nicholas_of_Tolentino\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"St. Nicholas of Tolentino\">St. Nicholas of Tolentino</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Bernardino_of_Siena\" title=\"Bernardino of Siena\">Bernardino of Siena</a>. Below, over a wood landscape, are the traditional depictions of  <a href=\"/wiki/St._Jerome\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"St. Jerome\">St. Jerome</a> with the lion, and <a href=\"/wiki/St._Sebastian\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"St. Sebastian\">St. Sebastian</a> struck by arrows. At the bottom, in the middle, is a tabernacle opening which once housed the Holy Sacrament. \n</p><p>The Madonna is taken from the same cartoon used by Perugino for the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Madonna_della_Consolazione_(Perugino)\" title=\"Madonna della Consolazione (Perugino)\">Madonna of the Consolation</a></i>, from the same period. Also, the use of colors is not typical of Perugino, and the work was perhaps executed mostly by his workshop, with the master adding just some touches.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Tezi_Altarpiece&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n</div>\n<table role=\"presentation\" class=\"mbox-small plainlinks sistersitebox\" style=\"background-color:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;color:#000\">\n<tbody><tr>\n<td class=\"mbox-image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/30px-Commons-logo.svg.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"40\" class=\"noviewer\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/45px-Commons-logo.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/59px-Commons-logo.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1024\" data-file-height=\"1376\" /></td>\n<td class=\"mbox-text plainlist\">Wikimedia Commons has media related to <i><b><a href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Pala_Tezi\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"commons:Category:Pala Tezi\">Pala Tezi</a></b></i>.</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sources\">Sources</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Tezi_Altarpiece&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Sources\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation book\">Garibaldi, Vittoria (2004). \"Perugino\". <i>Pittori del Rinascimento</i>. Florence: Scala. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"Internation